article.headline: O'Neal, Bryant, Malone, Stoudemire don't play
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- When the Phoenix Suns traded Stephon Marbury and Penny Hardaway to the New York Knicks two weeks ago, it appeared they were giving up on this season. Joe Johnson insists that's not the case. "We're not out there just to be playing, we're playing with a purpose," Johnson said after getting 26 points and 10 rebounds to lead the Suns to an 88-85 victory over the short-handed Los Angeles Lakers on Monday night. "I think a lot of people thought we were looking to the future," Johnson said. "We keep playing hard, we can get back in the playoff race." Johnson has scored 20, 26, 25 and 26 points in his last four games as the Suns established a season-high winning streak. The loss was just the third in 23 home games for the Lakers this season and their second in six games overall after a four-game losing streak. Jake Voskuhl had season-high totals of 18 points and 12 rebounds, and scored the Suns' final four points on two follow shots. "Jake stepped up tonight and that's what we need," Johnson said. Howard Eisley added 11 points and Shawn Marion and Leandro Barbosa had 10 each for the Suns. Kareem Rush led the Lakers with 18 points, and Bryon Russell added a season-high 17. Slava Medvedenko added 15 points, Gary Payton had 14 points, nine assists and a season-high eight rebounds, and Derek Fisher scored 13 points for Los Angeles, all but two in the final period. A jumper by Rush with 1:38 remaining tied it at 84, but a tip-in by Voskuhl 14 seconds later put the Suns ahead for good. Fisher's free throw drew the Lakers within a point, but Voskuhl made another follow shot with 47 seconds left to give the Suns an 88-85 lead. After Fisher missed from long range, Marion did the same for Phoenix, giving the Lakers possession with 8.2 seconds left. Fisher missed two 3-pointers after that. "We weren't sharp tonight -- our free-throw shooting reflected it down the stretch," Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. The Lakers shot 6-of-10 from the foul line in the fourth quarter, with Fisher 3-of-5. "I feel worse about that than missing those shots at the end," Fisher said. "The experiences we're going through now as a team, that's how you build character." The Lakers played without injured stars Shaquille O'Neal (strained right calf), Kobe Bryant (sprained right shoulder) and Karl Malone (sprained knee ligament). They also were without Horace Grant, who missed his third game while attending to his ailing father in Georgia. Grant had been starting in O'Neal's place. "We don't get rebounds and we don't make free throws at the end of the game, it's going to be tough to win," Payton said. "We've got to look past the injuries. "If we rebound the basketball tonight, we win easily." The Suns outrebounded the Lakers 47-40 despite playing without Amare Stoudemire, who reinjured his left ankle in the fourth quarter of Monday night's 96-92 victory over Portland. Stoudemire, the Suns' second-leading rebounder, missed 18 games before returning Jan. 9. The Suns led 63-61 entering the fourth quarter, and extended the lead to 74-68 before Fisher made the Lakers' first four-point play in 10 months and Payton added a layup, tying the game with 6:13 remaining. Neither team led by more than three after that. The teams combined to miss 10 shots at the beginning of the second half before Rush made a layup to put the Lakers on top 48-41. The Suns responded by scoring the next 12 points for a five-point lead. Marion capped the run with a 3-pointer -- his first field goal following eight misses. Marion, the Suns' leading scorer now that Marbury has been traded, wound up shooting 3-of-14 but had nine rebounds and four assists.

Game notes
The Suns placed F Antonio McDyess on the injured list because of left knee tendinitis and activated F-C Maciej Lampe. They acquired both players from New York earlier this month in the Marbury trade. ... The Lakers had won 12 straight games -- nine in the regular season and three in the playoffs -- against the Suns at Staples Center. ... The Lakers had also won the last five games between the teams. ... O'Neal, Bryant and Malone are expected to be with the Lakers during all or part of the three-game road trip that begins Wednesday night in Memphis. But none are expected to play on the trip, which concludes Saturday night in Utah. ... Jackson said he hadn't heard from Grant, who left for Georgia last Thursday, but expects the 38-year-old forward-center to rejoin the team in Memphis.
